  • A Matplotlib resource acompanies this part of the lab session. Follow along.
  • The official Matplotlib site has many useful goodies. Check it out.

2. What is Seaborn?¶

  • Seaborn is a Python data visualization library based on matplotlib.
  • Some of its attractive features are the beautiful default styles, simpler codes, and its ease of integration with the data structures of Pandas such as DataFrame. Note that Matplotlib predated Pandas by more than a decade. Seaborn which is based on Matplotlib is Pandas-aware.
  • It is a useful add-on to help you do exploratory analysis and understanding of data. As the saying goes, "A picture is worth a thousand words".
  • It can be installed from PyPI using pip or using conda (included as part of Anaconda distro). 
    pip install seaborn             # for pip 
conda install seaborn           # for conda

In [ ]:
In [9]:
# Create some data for plotting 

x = np.linspace(10, 20, 1000)
y = np.cumsum(np.random.randn(1000))
In [10]:
# plot the data using Matplotlib defaults

plt.plot(x, y)
plt.legend('A', loc='upper right');
In [13]:
# Now, let us do the same plotting using Seaborn
import seaborn as sns
#sns.set()             
sns.set(style="darkgrid")              # other styles: whitegrid, darkgrid, dark, etc

plt.plot(x, y)
plt.legend('A', loc='upper left');

A. Line Graph¶

In [21]:
# simple plot using lineplot() 

import warnings                          # to silence warning if need be
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

x = [i for i in range(20)]
y = [j*2 for j in range(20)]

sns.lineplot(y,x)

C. Distribution Plotting¶

  • The displot() function is useful to visualize distributions such as histograms.

  • This is useful for statistical analysis.

In [31]:
sns.displot(data=tipData, x="total_bill", col="day")             # try different x and col
Out[31]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1ab83501e50>

D. Pair Plot¶

  • There may arise a need to plot pairwise relationships in a dataset.
  • The pairplot() function serves this purpose. It uses scatterplot() for each pairing of the variables in the dataset, C(n,2) in number, and histplot() for the marginal plots along the diagonal.
In [34]:
#sns.pairplot(iris)
#iris
sns.pairplot(iris, hue="species")
Out[34]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x1ab884a9490>

  • Plot a pair plot using the tips dataset.

E. Box Plot¶

  • A.k.a. a box-and-whisker plot.

  • It is used to visualize distributions with respect to categories. A common use case is in times of comparing data between two groups.

In [35]:
sns.boxplot( iris['sepal_width'] )                                # meaning?
Out[35]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='sepal_width'>
In [36]:
sns.boxplot( x=iris['species'], y=iris['sepal_width'] )            # meaning?
Out[36]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='species', ylabel='sepal_width'>

Checkpoint!¶

  • Plot a box plot using the tips dataset.

F. Heat Map¶

  • It is a graphical representation where individual values of a matrix are represented as colors.
  • It plots rectangular data as a color-encoded matrix.
  • It helps to find patterns. A good use case is to visualize concentration of values.
In [39]:
# basic demo of heatmap

data = [ [1, 1, 1], [4, 1, 1], [1, 8, 1]] 

sns.heatmap(data)
Out[39]:
<AxesSubplot:>
In [40]:
# plot heatmap from an example dataset named "flights"

flights = sns.load_dataset("flights")

flights = flights.pivot("month", "year", "passengers")

sns.heatmap(flights)
Out[40]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='year', ylabel='month'>
